    <div class="author-note">
      <div class="author-avatar">R</div>
      <p><strong>Robert, founder of SnapProtein.</strong> I'm 64. I spent years thinking protein timing was about the post-workout window. Turns out the biggest timing mistake I was making had nothing to do with the gym — it was what I was eating at 7am. Or more accurately, what I wasn't eating.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="prose">

      <p>
        If you've spent any time in gyms or fitness spaces, you've heard the timing rules. Eat within 30 minutes of training. Hit protein every 2 hours. Don't let muscle break down. Most of it is built for competitive bodybuilders in their 20s. For men over 40 focused on maintaining muscle and staying strong, the hierarchy looks completely different.
      </p>

      <p>
        <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/what-120g-protein-looks-like/">Knowing what 120g of protein looks like across a day</a> is step one. Knowing <em>when</em> to eat it is what makes the system actually work.
      </p>

