          <div class="stat-label">lever: 30g at breakfast — most men skip it</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2>Two Myths Worth Killing First</h2>

      <p>
        Before we get to what actually matters, let's clear out what doesn't — because these two myths waste more mental energy than they're worth.
      </p>

      <div class="myth-grid">
        <div class="myth-card myth">
          <div class="mc-label">✗ Myth</div>
          <div class="mc-text"><strong>You must eat protein within 30 minutes of training</strong> or you'll miss the anabolic window and the workout is wasted.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="myth-card fact">
          <div class="mc-label">✓ Reality</div>
          <div class="mc-text">The window is closer to <strong>2 hours</strong>. If you trained and had a protein-containing meal within that window, you're fine. For men over 40 who aren't competing, this is a non-issue.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="myth-card myth">
          <div class="mc-label">✗ Myth</div>
          <div class="mc-text"><strong>You need to eat protein every 2 hours</strong> to prevent muscle breakdown and keep synthesis elevated all day.</div>
        </div>
        <div class="myth-card fact">
          <div class="mc-label">✓ Reality</div>
          <div class="mc-text">Three to four meals with <strong>25–35g each</strong> is sufficient. Extreme meal frequency adds stress without meaningful benefit for most men over 40.</div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        Both myths have the same root: they were built around competitive athletes trying to optimize every last variable. You're not optimizing for a stage. You're optimizing for the next 20 years of being strong and healthy. The target is different, and so is the strategy.
      </p>

      <div class="link-box">
        <strong>Why timing matters more after 40</strong>
        <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/anabolic-resistance-after-40/">Anabolic resistance explained — why your muscles respond differently to protein after 40 →</a>
      </div>

      <h2>Protein Timing After 40 — Ranked by Real Impact</h2>

      <p>
        Here's the honest hierarchy. Not everything matters equally. Focus on the top two and you've covered most of what moves the needle.
      </p>

      <!-- TIMING CARDS -->
      <div class="timing-grid">

        <div class="timing-card">
          <div class="rank-badge">#1</div>
          <div class="tc-body">
            <div class="tc-title">Breakfast — the make-or-break window</div>
            <div class="tc-impact impact-high">Impact: Very High</div>
            <div class="tc-desc">Most men over 40 eat 8–12g of protein at breakfast (cereal, toast, coffee) and spend the rest of the day playing catch-up. Getting 30g at breakfast activates muscle protein synthesis early, sets the distribution for the day, and directly overcomes the anabolic resistance that gets worse with age. One cup of Greek yogurt and 2–3 eggs gets you there in 90 seconds.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timing-card">
          <div class="rank-badge">#2</div>
          <div class="tc-body">
            <div class="tc-title">Distribution — spread it, don't stack it</div>
            <div class="tc-impact impact-high">Impact: Very High</div>
            <div class="tc-desc">120g of protein eaten across 3–4 meals is dramatically more effective than 120g eaten mostly at dinner. Your muscles can only use ~25–35g per sitting for synthesis — the rest gets used for energy. Front-loading dinner is the single most common protein timing mistake men over 40 make. Three meals at 30g each beats one large protein meal every time.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timing-card">
          <div class="rank-badge">#3</div>
          <div class="tc-body">
            <div class="tc-title">Before bed — the overnight window most men ignore</div>
            <div class="tc-impact impact-med">Impact: Moderate</div>
            <div class="tc-desc">Sleep is your longest fasting period — typically 7–9 hours with no protein input. Pre-sleep protein (casein specifically) digests slowly and provides a sustained amino acid supply during that window. Cottage cheese is the easiest source: 25g of protein, slow-digesting, and something you can eat cold in 2 minutes. Not required, but it's one of the highest-return habits you can add once the basics are dialed in.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="timing-card">
          <div class="rank-badge">#4</div>
          <div class="tc-body">
            <div class="tc-title">Post-workout — real but overrated</div>
            <div class="tc-impact impact-med">Impact: Moderate (if you train)</div>
            <div class="tc-desc">Post-workout protein does matter — resistance training opens a window of elevated muscle protein synthesis that protein can amplify. But the window is 2 hours, not 30 minutes, and if your next meal falls within that window you're already covered. You don't need a shake in the gym parking lot. Have your next planned meal and move on.</div>
          </div>
        </div>

      </div>

      <div class="pull-quote">
        <p>"The timing mistake most men over 40 are making isn't post-workout. It's breakfast. Fix that first."</p>
      </div>

      <h2>What This Looks Like as a Full Day</h2>

      <p>
        Here's how the timing principles map to an actual day. Same foods you'd find on <a href="https://snapprotein.com/blog/high-protein-grocery-list-men-over-40/">a real grocery list</a>, structured around the four timing windows that matter.
      </p>

      <!-- SAMPLE DAY -->
      <div class="sample-day">
        <h3>Timing-Optimized Day — 120g+ Protein</h3>
        <div class="meal-row">
          <span class="meal-time">7am Breakfast</span>
