          <span class="meal-grams">51g</span>
        </div>
        <div class="meal-row">
          <span class="meal-time">6pm Dinner</span>
          <span class="meal-desc">5oz ground beef + vegetables</span>
          <span class="meal-grams">35g</span>
        </div>
        <div class="meal-row">
          <span class="meal-time">9pm Before bed</span>
          <span class="meal-desc">½ cup cottage cheese (casein, slow-digesting)</span>
          <span class="meal-grams">13g</span>
        </div>
        <div class="meal-total">
          <span>Daily total:</span>
          <em>134g</em>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p>
        That's four protein signals spread across the day — each hitting or approaching the 25–35g threshold where muscle protein synthesis is meaningfully activated. No eating every 2 hours. No obsessing over post-workout windows. Just consistent distribution from morning to night.
      </p>

      <h2>The Before-Bed Window — Worth Doing if You're Not Already</h2>

      <p>
        This one surprises most men because it sounds like something bodybuilders do. But the science on pre-sleep protein is solid and the practical version is simple: a small serving of cottage cheese before bed.
      </p>

      <p>
        Cottage cheese is high in casein protein, which digests slowly over 5–7 hours — exactly the window your muscles go without protein during sleep. A half cup adds 12–14g. A full cup adds 25g. Either way it's a meaningful overnight signal for muscle protein synthesis that most men are leaving completely untapped.
      </p>

      <p>
        It's not required. If you're already hitting 120g+ across your three main meals, you're in good shape. But if you're consistently falling 10–20g short by dinner, this is the easiest fix on the list — no cooking, no planning, 30 seconds before you brush your teeth.
      </p>

