        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>What is the best time to eat protein after 40?</h3>
          <p>The single highest-impact timing move for men over 40 is getting 30g of protein at breakfast. Most men are protein-light in the morning and try to catch up at dinner — which is far less effective. A high-protein breakfast sets the distribution for the whole day and overcomes the anabolic resistance that increases with age.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Does the anabolic window matter after 40?</h3>
          <p>The strict 30-minute post-workout window is largely a myth for men over 40 who are not competitive athletes. Current research shows the window is closer to 2 hours. For most men over 40, total daily protein and distribution across meals matters far more than precise post-workout timing.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Should men over 40 eat protein before bed?</h3>
          <p>Yes — pre-sleep protein is one of the most underused timing strategies for men over 40. Casein protein (found in cottage cheese) digests slowly overnight, providing a sustained amino acid supply during the longest fasting period of the day. 25–40g of cottage cheese before bed supports overnight muscle protein synthesis without requiring any preparation.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Do you need to eat protein every 2 hours after 40?</h3>
          <p>No. Eating every 2 hours is unnecessary and impractical. Three to four meals per day, each with 25–35g of protein, is sufficient to maximize muscle protein synthesis throughout the day. The research supports meal distribution, not extreme meal frequency.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
          <h3>Is breakfast or dinner more important for protein after 40?</h3>
          <p>Breakfast. Most men over 40 load protein at dinner and under-eat it in the morning — which is the least effective distribution pattern. Getting 30g at breakfast activates muscle protein synthesis early and makes the rest of the day far easier to manage.</p>
